<subSubSection id="C3207CD4FFE6FFC6FF7AFF22945DFC39" pageId="2" pageNumber="202" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B852F5FFFE6FFC6FF7AFF229097FE95" blockId="2.[151,1437,223,970]" pageId="2" pageNumber="202">
The family 
<taxonomicName id="4C3A54DCFFE6FFC6FEF5FF229087FF09" authorityName="Gutu" authorityYear="1981" box="[280,442,223,249]" family="Parapseudidae" pageId="2" pageNumber="202" rank="family">Parapseudidae</taxonomicName>
was established by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAB52AEFFE6FFC6FD7BFF229222FF09" author="Gutu, M." box="[662,799,223,249]" pageId="2" pageNumber="202" pagination="81 - 108" refId="ref13622" refString="Gutu, M. (1981) A new contribution to the systematics and phylogeny of the suborder Monokonophora (Crustacea, Tanaidacea). Travaux du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle &quot; Grigore Antipa &quot;, 23, 81 - 108." type="journal article" year="1981">Guţu (1981)</bibRefCitation>
to include those apseudomorphan genera lacking a spiniform apophysis on the coxa of the first pereopods. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAB52AEFFE6FFC6FD26FEFE9269FEED" author="Gutu, M." box="[715,852,259,285]" pageId="2" pageNumber="202" pagination="43 - 70" refId="ref13726" refString="Gutu, M. (2008) A revision of the family Parapseudidae, with description of a new tribe and three genera. The diagnoses and the key of the superspecific taxa (Crustacea: Tanaidacea: Apseudomorpha). Travaux du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle &quot; Grigore Antipa &quot;, 51, 43 - 70." type="journal article" year="2008">Guţu (2008)</bibRefCitation>
revised the family and presented a key to the known genera. Since this revision three genera have been added to the family (
<bibRefCitation id="EFAB52AEFFE6FFC6FC52FEDA9426FEB1" author="Heard, R. W. &amp; Morales-Nunez, A. G." box="[959,1307,295,321]" pageId="2" pageNumber="202" pagination="49 - 63" refId="ref13914" refString="Heard, R. W. &amp; Morales-Nunez, A. G. (2011) Akanthoparapseudes alfaroae, a new genus and new species of apseudomorphan tanaidacean (Crustacea: Malacostraca: Peracarida) from Puerto Rico coastal waters. Zootaxa, 3111, 49 - 63." type="journal article" year="2011">
<collectingCountry id="F32D6FCFFFE6FFC6FC52FEDA9538FEB1" box="[959,1029,295,321]" name="Heard Island and McDonald Islands" pageId="2" pageNumber="202">Heard</collectingCountry>
&amp; Morales-Núñez 2011
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAB52AEFFE6FFC6FACAFEDA91CAFE95" author="Bamber, R. N. &amp; Chatterjee, T. &amp; Marshall, D. J." pageId="2" pageNumber="202" pagination="71 - 88" refId="ref12253" refString="Bamber, R. N., Chatterjee, T. &amp; Marshall, D. J. (2012) Inshore apseudomorph tanaidaceans (Crustacea: Peracarida) from Brunei: new records and new species. Zootaxa, 3520 (1), 71 - 88. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3520.1.3" type="journal article" year="2012">
Bamber 
<emphasis id="B94EF34DFFE6FFC6FA65FED59189FE95" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="202">et al.</emphasis>
2012
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAB52AEFFE6FFC6FEEFFEB690A3FE95" author="Bamber, R. N." box="[258,414,331,357]" pageId="2" pageNumber="202" pagination="401 - 441" refId="ref12140" refString="Bamber, R. N. (2013) Tanaidaceans from Brunei, IV. The families Kalliapseudidae, Pagurapseudopsidae, Parapseudidae and Apseudidae (Crustacea: Peracarida: Tanaidacea: Apseudomorpha), with descriptions of a new genus and six new species. Zootaxa, 3734 (4), 401 - 441. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3734.4.1" type="journal article" year="2013">Bamber 2013</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B852F5FFFE6FFC6FF2AFE9295C7FDCD" blockId="2.[151,1437,223,970]" pageId="2" pageNumber="202">
Parapseudids appear to be mainly restricted to the tropical and temperate coastal and shelf waters and less than 10% of the nominal species are presently known from depths greater than 
<quantity id="4CC282BAFFE6FFC6FC3CFE6E952AFE5E" box="[977,1047,403,430]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="202" unit="m" value="200.0">200 m</quantity>
(see 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAB52AEFFE6FFC6FBBCFE6E95F6FE5D" author="Gutu, M." box="[1105,1227,403,429]" pageId="2" pageNumber="202" pagination="43 - 70" refId="ref13726" refString="Gutu, M. (2008) A revision of the family Parapseudidae, with description of a new tribe and three genera. The diagnoses and the key of the superspecific taxa (Crustacea: Tanaidacea: Apseudomorpha). Travaux du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle &quot; Grigore Antipa &quot;, 51, 43 - 70." type="journal article" year="2008">Guţu 2008</bibRefCitation>
, p. 45). At present, including the two new genera and the new species from the Southwest GoM established in this paper, the subfamily 
<taxonomicName id="4C3A54DCFFE6FFC6FF7AFE269004FE05" authorityName="Gutu" authorityYear="2008" box="[151,313,475,501]" pageId="2" pageNumber="202" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Parapseudinae">Parapseudinae</taxonomicName>
now contains 70 species representing 20 genera and the Pakistanapseudinae with 24 species representing 10 genera (
<bibRefCitation id="EFAB52AEFFE6FFC6FE87FE029320FDE9" author="Anderson, G." box="[362,541,511,537]" pageId="2" pageNumber="202" refId="ref11807" refString="Anderson, G. (2020) Tanaidacea - Forty Years of Scholarship. Version. 3.0. January 2020. Available from: http: // aquila. usm. edu / tanaids 30 / 5 / (accessed 15 February 2022)" type="journal volume" year="2020">Anderson 2020</bibRefCitation>
). The two subfamilies are primarily distinguished from each other by the length, width, and armature of the pleonites in relation to the pereon, and the morphology of their pleopods.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B852F5FFFE6FFC6FF2AFDBA90F8FCCA" blockId="2.[151,1437,223,970]" pageId="2" pageNumber="202">
Although relatively little is known of the ecology of the Pakistanapseudinae, its species usually occur in high salinities on soft-bottom substrata at mid and lower latitudes. At present, no representatives are reported from lowsalinity inshore habitats, similar to those occupied by members of the 
<emphasis id="B94EF34DFFE6FFC6FC28FD729418FD59" box="[965,1317,655,682]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="202">
<taxonomicName id="4C3A54DCFFE6FFC6FC28FD729562FD59" authority="Drumm &amp; Heard, 2022" authorityName="Drumm &amp; Heard" authorityYear="2022" box="[965,1119,655,681]" class="Malacostraca" family="Parapseudidae" genus="Discapseudes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Tanaidacea" pageId="2" pageNumber="219" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="n.g.">Discapseudes</taxonomicName>
-Halmyrapseudes
</emphasis>
Complex. Many of the morphological characters exhibited by the pakistanapseudins appear to be plesiomorphic and distinctive (e.g., sexually dimorphic male antennule of some taxa), suggesting that this group, like that of the Complex, may have become differentiated and morphologically defined during the Permian prior to the Permian-Triassic Extinction (P-TEx) events.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B852F5FFFE6FFC6FF2AFCB9945DFC39" blockId="2.[151,1437,223,970]" pageId="2" pageNumber="202">
In reviewing the literature for taxonomic and morphological criteria related to the designation of the new Mexican parapseudid genus, we conclude that the Australian species 
<emphasis id="B94EF34DFFE6FFC6FC8AFC9A953CFC71" box="[871,1025,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="202">Longiflagrum</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C3A54DCFFE6FFC6FBE5FC9A9415FC71" authority="(Boesch, 1973)" authorityName="Drumm &amp; Heard" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Boesch" baseAuthorityYear="1973" box="[1032,1320,871,897]" genus="Pseudolongiflagrum" pageId="2" pageNumber="202" rank="species" species="caeruleus">
<emphasis id="B94EF34DFFE6FFC6FBE5FC9A9548FC71" box="[1032,1141,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="202">caeruleus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFAB52AEFFE6FFC6FB69FC9A941DFC71" author="Boesch, D. F." box="[1156,1312,871,897]" pageId="2" pageNumber="202" pagination="168 - 188" refId="ref12421" refString="Boesch, D. F. (1973) Three new tanaids (Crustacea, Tanaidacea) from southern Queensland. Pacific Science, 27 (2), 168 - 188." type="journal article" year="1973">Boesch, 1973</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
exhibits a unique combination of characters that warrant the establishment of a monotypic genus to receive it. A dichotomous key to the 20 genera of the subfamily 
<taxonomicName id="4C3A54DCFFE6FFC6FDADFC5293D8FC39" authorityName="Gutu" authorityYear="2008" box="[576,741,943,969]" pageId="2" pageNumber="202" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Parapseudinae">Parapseudinae</taxonomicName>
, including those two diagnosed here, is presented below.
</paragraph>
